---
// src/pages/resources/ai-risk-profile-case-study.astro
// Case study — the full Quirgs AI Risk Profile self-assessment. Terminal (TUI)
// styling inherited from BaseLayout, mirroring the /skills/[slug] detail-page
// structure and the publish-bundle-stress-test case study's own conventions.
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import NavBlock from "../../components/NavBlock.astro";

const waveResults = [
  {
    wave: "Wave 1 — quirgs-compliance",
    scope: "7 skills, 48 fixtures",
    baseline: "3 / 7 clean on first run",
    result: "7 / 7 verified clean after fixes",
  },
  {
    wave: "Wave 2 — quirgs-publish",
    scope: "8 skills, 40 fixtures",
    baseline: "1 / 8 clean on first run",
    result: "9 / 9 targeted defects verified clean after two fix rounds",
  },
];

const frameworkResults = [
  {
    area: "NIST AI RMF (Govern / Map / Measure / Manage)",
    finding: "Full four-function assessment against our own platform",
    status: "Policy, risk register, incident playbook, and misuse tabletop closed the gaps found",
  },
  {
    area: "EU AI Act",
    finding: "Formal risk-tier classification of the Quirgs platform itself",
    status: "Classified Minimal Risk — decision-support tooling, not an autonomous high-risk system",
  },
  {
    area: "ISO/IEC 42001",
    finding: "Gap analysis against the AI management system standard",
    status: "Scoped gaps identified and tracked to closure alongside the NIST work",
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Quirgs AI Risk Profile — Self-Assessment Case Study"
  description="We ran NIST AI RMF, the EU AI Act, ISO 42001, and our own skill-validation harness against Quirgs itself — all 15 skills across both bundles. Here's what a governance company finds when it turns the framework on its own product."
  terminalPath="~/resources/ai-risk-profile-case-study"
>
  <NavBlock currentPath="/resources/" />

  <!-- Back to resources listing -->
  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-blue">&larr;</span>&nbsp;<a href="/resources/"
      >back to resources</a
    >
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="line">
    <span class="prompt">admin@quirgs</span><span class="path">~/resources</span
    ><span class="text-bright">$</span>&nbsp;cat ai-risk-profile-case-study.md
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <!-- Header block -->
  <div class="detail-header">
    <h1 class="text-bright">The Quirgs AI Risk Profile — Self-Assessment Case Study</h1>
    <p class="tagline">
      We ran the same frameworks and the same validation harness we sell
      against our own platform — both skill bundles, 15 skills, 88 fixtures.
      Most of it failed on the first pass.
    </p>
    <div class="badges-row">
      <span class="badge">July 2026</span>
      <span class="badge status-badge status-live">[15 SKILLS · 2 BUNDLES]</span>
      <span class="badge status-badge status-live">[NIST · EU AI ACT · ISO 42001]</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Problem We Were Solving</h2>
  <p>
    Quirgs sells governance: risk classification, compliance checkpoints,
    output validation. That premise only holds if the same rigor applies to
    Quirgs itself. So we ran a full self-assessment — the complete NIST AI RMF
    framework, an EU AI Act classification, an ISO 42001 gap analysis, and a
    clean-room validation harness against every skill in both bundles. This
    is a summary of what a governance company finds when it turns its own
    framework on its own product.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Governance Assessment</h2>
  <p>
    Before testing individual skill outputs, we assessed the platform itself
    against the three frameworks our skills evaluate for customers.
  </p>

  <div class="results-table">
    <div class="results-header">
      <span class="col-test text-bright">FRAMEWORK</span>
      <span class="col-result text-bright">OUTCOME</span>
    </div>
    <div class="divider-row"><span class="divider-line"></span></div>
    {
      frameworkResults.map((row) => (
        <div class="result-row">
          <span class="col-test">{row.area}</span>
          <span class="col-result">
            {row.finding} — {row.status}
          </span>
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <p>
    The NIST assessment surfaced real gaps at baseline: no formal risk
    register, no incident response plan, no structured process for thinking
    through how a correct-looking-but-wrong output could cause harm. Each of
    those became a governance artifact — a risk register with specific,
    scored entries; an incident playbook with defined severity tiers; a
    misuse tabletop that walked through the actual failure modes and fed
    findings back into the register. None of this was theoretical. Every
    finding below traces back to a line in that register.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Skill-by-Skill Validation — Two Waves</h2>
  <p>
    Governance frameworks establish structure. They don't tell you whether a
    specific skill produces a correct answer. For that, we built a
    clean-room evaluation harness: fixture inputs with no answer key attached
    are handed to a fresh session that has never seen the reference answer;
    a separate pass grades the raw output against a rubric with defined
    automatic-failure conditions. The session that writes the reference
    answers never grades against them. That separation is the point — it's
    the difference between a real test and a company grading its own
    homework.
  </p>
  <p>We ran that harness against both bundles, in two waves.</p>

  <div class="results-table">
    <div class="results-header">
      <span class="col-test text-bright">WAVE</span>
      <span class="col-result text-bright">RESULT</span>
    </div>
    <div class="divider-row"><span class="divider-line"></span></div>
    {
      waveResults.map((row) => (
        <div class="result-row">
          <span class="col-test">
            {row.wave}
            <br />
            <span class="col-scope">{row.scope}</span>
          </span>
          <span class="col-result">
            Baseline: {row.baseline}
            <br />
            {row.result}
          </span>
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <p>
    The defects found were not formatting nitpicks. Wave 1 surfaced a
    regulatory-substance error — a skill failed to correctly classify a
    prohibited-practice scenario — alongside a systemic gap where the
    advisory disclaimer didn't appear on every response, only the final
    formatted output. Wave 2, run against the newer publish bundle, found an
    AI-involvement classifier that computed the wrong risk tier for an
    unauthorized voice clone (a case where the reasoning was correct but the
    number wasn't), an orchestrator that hedged around its own hard-stop rule
    for blocked releases, a required copyright field that wasn't actually
    enforced as blocking, and a dormancy calculation that fired one quarter
    too early. Six of the eight publish skills were missing the advisory
    disclaimer on non-final responses; one had no disclaimer infrastructure
    at all.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Fix That Didn't Hold — And How We Caught It</h2>
  <p>
    One finding is worth telling in detail, because the first fix looked
    complete and wasn't.
  </p>
  <p>
    The publish-bundle orchestrator has a hard rule: if a release is blocked
    pending resolution of a compliance issue, it stops — no partial
    workaround, no "ship to the clear platforms and fix the rest later." The
    baseline run found the skill stating that rule and then floating exactly
    that kind of workaround anyway. The first fix added explicit language
    forbidding it, with one narrow exception for cases where a genuine
    per-platform status breakdown already existed elsewhere in the
    conversation.
  </p>
  <p>
    On independent re-verification, the exception clause turned out to be the
    loophole. Given a description that merely sounded platform-specific — no
    actual breakdown present — the model used the exception as license to
    construct one anyway and suggest the workaround. Same defect, new
    phrasing, one fix cycle later.
  </p>
  <p>
    The second fix removed the exception entirely. No inferred breakdowns,
    ever — only a verbatim status already stated elsewhere. Re-verified
    independently a second time, against the same input that had broken it
    twice before. It held.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">A Second Kind of Finding: Model Drift</h2>
  <p>
    Not every finding was a skill defect. Re-running the NIST assessment
    skill under a newer model produced a different, subtly wrong result on
    the same input that a prior model handled correctly — the newer model
    marked several subcategories as confidently failing where the correct
    answer, given no evidence either way, was "insufficient information."
    The skill's own text hadn't changed. The underlying model had. We
    verified this with a controlled comparison (identical skill definition,
    two model versions) before concluding it was drift rather than a defect,
    and it's now a monitored, logged risk rather than an assumption. This is
    a different category of finding than a code bug — it's evidence that
    "we tested it once" isn't the same claim as "it stays correct."
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">What This Demonstrates</h2>
  <p>Three things worth noting for anyone deciding whether to trust this process:</p>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">The methodology is repeatable, across the whole
    platform.</span> Clean-room validation isn't a one-time audit of one
    bundle — it's a harness we've now run against both, and it caught
    something different in each: a regulatory-substance error, a disclaimer
    gap, a hard-stop rule with a hedge built into it, and a model-drift
    instance that had nothing to do with our own code at all.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">A fix that looks complete isn't verified until
    it's re-run.</span> The blocked-release case is the whole argument for
    re-verification as a distinct step from fixing. A team that ships a fix
    and calls it done, without checking again, would have missed this.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">The defects were real, and they were ours.</span>
    Every finding above came from our own shipped product, found by our own
    methodology, in places that would have mattered to a real user relying on
    the output. A governance practice that only ever finds other people's
    problems isn't one you should trust with yours.
  </p>

  <div class="detail-footer">
    <p><span class="label">PUBLISHED:</span> July 2026</p>
    <p><span class="label">SCOPE:</span> 15 skills across 2 bundles, 88 fixtures, 2 eval waves</p>
    <p><span class="label">FRAMEWORKS:</span> NIST AI RMF · EU AI Act (Minimal Risk) · ISO/IEC 42001</p>
    <p>
      <span class="label">BUNDLES:</span>
      <a href="/bundles/">quirgs-compliance &amp; quirgs-publish</a>
    </p>
  </div>

  <p class="signoff text-main">Quirgs · Governance first. Build accordingly.</p>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .results-table {
    width: 100%;
    font-size: 0.86rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 12px 0 24px;
  }

  .results-header,
  .result-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 32% 1fr;
    gap: 0 16px;
    align-items: baseline;
  }

  .results-header {
    margin-bottom: 2px;
  }

  .divider-row {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .divider-line {
    display: block;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--term-border);
    width: 100%;
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
  }

  .result-row {
    padding: 8px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--term-border);
  }

  .result-row:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .col-test {
    color: var(--text-bright);
  }

  .col-scope {
    color: var(--text-main);
    opacity: 0.75;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
  }

  .signoff {
    margin-top: 32px;
    padding-top: 16px;
    border-top: 1px dashed var(--term-border);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.8;
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .results-header,
    .result-row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .results-header .col-result {
      display: none;
    }

    .col-result {
      margin-top: 4px;
    }
  }
</style>
